    Review the node's system logs (e.g., /var/log/syslog or /var/log/messages) for any errors or warnings.
    Verify that the kubelet service is running and healthy on the node.
    Check for network connectivity issues between the node and the Kubernetes control plane.
    Inspect resource usage (CPU, memory, disk) on the node to ensure it is not overloaded.
    Restart the kubelet service or reboot the node if necessary to restore its readiness state.

13. What is the difference between Liveness Probe and Readiness Probe in Kubernetes?
    A Liveness Probe checks if a container is still running and healthy. If the liveness probe fails, Kubernetes will restart the container to recover from a potential failure.

    A Readiness Probe checks if a container is ready to accept traffic. If the readiness probe fails, Kubernetes will remove the pod from the service endpoints, preventing it from receiving traffic until it becomes ready again.

